{ FARMING IN LEIGH AND BRANSFORD (2)}
Most farms extend to between 250 and 350 acres, but nowadays comparat_ ively few of the local people are employed on the land. Until about twenty years ago hop pickers from the Black Country came annually and were housed in 'barracks', but the advent of modern machinery for picking and harvesting and the changes in land use have brought about a gradual decline in the number of agricultural workers, both on a permanent and casual basis.
Today the casual pickers are those who come in their cars to pick fruit and vegetables for home freezing. 'Pick-Your-Own' notices sprout along the roadsides and farmers make provision for car parking and for weighing out the picked produce.
